SIMPLE: fur
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fur
<hw>Fur</hw> <pr>(f⟦ucir⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>furre</ets>, OF. <ets>forre</ets>, <ets>fuerre</ets>, sheath, case,
of German origin; cf. OHG. <ets>fuotar</ets> lining, case, G.
<ets>futter</ets>; akin to Icel. <ets>f⟦omac⟧⟦edh⟧r</ets> lining, Goth.
<ets>f⟦omac⟧dr</ets>, scabbard; cf. Skr. <ets>p⟦amac⟧tra</ets> vessel,
dish. The German and Icel. words also have the sense, <ets>fodder</ets>,
but this was probably a different word originally. Cf. <er>Fodder</er>
food, <er>Fother</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, <er>Forel</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The short, fine, soft hair of certain animals,
growing thick on the skin, and distinguished from the hair, which is
longer and coarser.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The skins of certain wild animals with the fur;
peltry; <as>as, a cargo of furs</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Strips of dressed skins with fur, used on garments
for warmth or for ornament.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Articles of clothing made of fur;
<as>as, a set of <ex>furs</ex> for a lady (a collar, tippet, or cape,
muff, etc.)</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wrapped up in my <qex>furs</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Lady M. W.
Montagu.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Any coating considered as resembling fur</def>; as:
<sd>(a)</sd> <def>A coat of morbid matter collected on the tongue in
persons affected with fever.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The soft, downy
covering on the skin of a peach.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The deposit
formed on the interior of boilers and other vessels by hard
water.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>One of several patterns or diapers
used as tinctures. There are nine in all, or, according to some writers,
only six.</def> <rj><au>See Tincture.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fur</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fur
<hw>Fur</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to furs;
bearing or made of fur; <as>as, a <ex>fur</ex> cap; the <ex>fur</ex>
trade.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fur seal</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>one of several
species of seals of the genera <gen>Callorhinus</gen> and
<gen>Arclocephalus</gen>, inhabiting the North Pacific and the Antarctic
oceans. They have a coat of fine and soft fur which is highly prized.
The northern fur seal (<spn>Callorhinus ursinus</spn>) breeds in vast
numbers on the Prybilov Islands, off the coast of Alaska; -- called also
<altname>sea bear</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fur</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fur
<hw>Fur</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Furred</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Furring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To line, face, or
cover with fur; <as>as, <ex>furred</ex> robes</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧You
<xex>fur</xex> your gloves with reason.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cover with morbid matter, as the
tongue.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>To nail small strips of board or
larger scantling upon, in order to make a level surface for lathing or
boarding, or to provide for a space or interval back of the plastered or
boarded surface, as inside an outer wall, by way of protection against
damp.</def> <rj><au>Gwill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Furacious</ent>⟦br⟧
